# CLAUDE.md - API Platform Example (Payments)

> This is a filled-in example showing what CLAUDE.md looks like for a developer-facing API platform.
> Copy the blank template from CLAUDE.md.example and adapt it to your product.

## Shipwright

Type `/start` at the beginning of a session to launch the Shipwright orchestrator.

## Product

- **Name:** PayRoute
- **Category:** Payment orchestration API for marketplaces and platforms
- **Stage:** Growth (Series B, 3 years post-launch, 340 customers)
- **Target users:** Engineering leads and heads of payments at marketplaces and platforms ($10M-$500M GMV) who need multi-PSP routing, split payments, and compliance tooling
- **Core job-to-be-done:** Let platforms route payments across multiple processors, manage seller payouts, and handle compliance without building payment infrastructure from scratch

## Key Metrics

| Metric | Current Value | Target | Timeframe |
|---|---|---|---|
| North Star: Monthly payment volume processed | $2.1B | $4B | Q4 2026 |
| API uptime | 99.97% | 99.99% | Q3 2026 |
| Time to first live transaction (new customer) | 18 days | 7 days | Q3 2026 |
| Net revenue retention | 132% | 140% | Q4 2026 |

## Strategic Priorities (Current Quarter)

1. **Smart routing:** Automatically route transactions to the processor with the highest approval rate for a given card type, geography, and amount. This is the top-requested feature from customers processing >$50M/month.
2. **Developer experience overhaul:** Rewrite docs, add interactive API explorer, ship SDKs for Python and Go (currently only Node and Ruby). Median time-to-first-transaction is 18 days and it should be under a week.
3. **SOC 2 Type II:** Complete audit. 40% of enterprise pipeline is gated on this.

## What We're NOT Doing

- Consumer payments. We're infrastructure for platforms, not a Stripe competitor for direct merchants.
- Crypto/stablecoin payments. Regulatory complexity isn't worth it for our market segment yet.
- Building our own acquiring capability. We orchestrate across existing PSPs.

## Personas

### Payments Lead Patricia
- **Role:** Head of Payments or Payments Engineer. Owns PSP relationships, payment routing logic, and payout operations. Reports to VP Engineering or CTO.
- **Goals:** Increase approval rates, reduce processing costs by routing intelligently, consolidate reporting across PSPs, stay PCI compliant without it consuming her team.
- **Pain points:** Managing 3 PSPs with custom integrations each. No single view of transaction success rates across processors. Building retry and fallback logic in-house is fragile.
- **How she evaluates tools:** Wants to see API docs before a sales call. Needs sandbox with realistic test data. Asks about latency percentiles, not averages. Checks status page history.

### Platform CTO Tom
- **Role:** CTO at a marketplace. Signs off on infrastructure decisions. Cares about payments as a business-critical dependency, not a feature he wants to build.
- **Goals:** Stop his team from building and maintaining payment infrastructure. Reduce vendor lock-in to any single PSP.
- **Pain points:** Current Stripe-only setup means no leverage on pricing and no fallback if Stripe has an outage. His team has spent 6 months building split payment logic that still has edge cases.

## Competitors

| Competitor | Type | Our Advantage | Their Advantage |
|---|---|---|---|
| Stripe Connect | Direct | Multi-PSP routing, lower lock-in, smart routing | Developer brand, ecosystem, single-vendor simplicity |
| Spreedly | Direct | Better marketplace features (splits, payouts, compliance), simpler pricing | Wider PSP coverage, longer track record |
| In-house builds | Indirect | Maintained by us, not by their payments team | Full control, no vendor dependency |

## Conventions

- **User stories:** "As a [persona], I want [action] so that [outcome]"
- **PRD format:** Working Backwards, with a technical addendum for API contract changes
- **Prioritization:** RICE scoring, with reach = number of customer accounts affected
- **Roadmap style:** Now / Next / Later, shared publicly on docs site
- **Sprint cadence:** 2-week sprints
- **Definition of Done:** API changes deployed to sandbox, integration tests green, docs updated, changelog entry written, migration guide if breaking

## Tools & Integrations

- **Project management:** Linear
- **Documentation:** GitBook (public docs) + Notion (internal)
- **Analytics:** Datadog (infrastructure) + Metabase (business metrics on Postgres)
- **Communication:** Slack
- **Design:** Figma (internal tools and docs)
- **API testing:** Postman collections maintained alongside code

## Glossary

| Term | Definition |
|---|---|
| PSP | Payment service provider (Stripe, Adyen, Braintree, etc.) |
| GMV | Gross merchandise value, total transaction volume across a platform |
| Smart routing | Automatically selecting the best PSP for a transaction based on approval probability |
| Split payment | A single transaction divided across multiple recipients (platform + sellers) |
| Payout | Disbursement of funds from the platform to individual sellers |
| Sandbox | Test environment with simulated PSP responses for integration development |
